{"sha": "a7710eff06d52b861c618e91a5c1f490f4796f4f", "node_id": "MDY6Q29tbWl0NzI0NzEyOmE3NzEwZWZmMDZkNTJiODYxYzYxOGU5MWE1YzFmNDkwZjQ3OTZmNGY=", "commit": {"author": {"name": "Alex Crichton", "email": "alex@alexcrichton.com", "date": "2016-12-20T19:16:32Z"}, "committer": {"name": "Alex Crichton", "email": "alex@alexcrichton.com", "date": "2016-12-20T20:59:02Z"}, "message": "Rollup merge of #38315 - jonhoo:better-E0309, r=pnkfelix\n\nExpand E0309 explanation with motivating example\n\nI recently started reading @Gankro's \"[Learning Rust With Entirely Too Many Linked Lists](http://cglab.ca/~abeinges/blah/too-many-lists/book/README.html)\", and came across [a part](http://cglab.ca/~abeinges/blah/too-many-lists/book/second-iter.html) where he comes across `E0309`, and after showing `rustc --explain E0309` prompty says\n\n> This is dumb. I think it's dumb. You have to do it.\n\nHumor aside, I think this says something about the current explanation being somewhat lacking.\n\nThis patch introduces a motivating example saying why `T: 'a` is a necessary restriction. Hopefully, this will help new Rustaceans understand why leaving out the `'a` bound on `T` might lead to broken code.", "tree": {"sha": "510834a3ea6139ff42a98db41b82ecc905a03727", "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rust-lang/rust/git/trees/510834a3ea6139ff42a98db41b82ecc905a03727"}, "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rust-lang/rust/git/commits/a7710eff06d52b861c618e91a5c1f490f4796f4f", "comment_count": 0, "verification": {"verified": false, "reason": "unsigned", "signature": null, "payload": null}}, "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rust-lang/rust/commits/a7710eff06d52b861c618e91a5c1f490f4796f4f", "html_url": "https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/commit/a7710eff06d52b861c618e91a5c1f490f4796f4f", "comments_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rust-lang/rust/commits/a7710eff06d52b861c618e91a5c1f490f4796f4f/comments", "author": {"login": "alexcrichton", "id": 64996, "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjY0OTk2", "avatar_url": "htt